ity. It handles OCSP stapling through the OcspStapleAction enum and methods like ocspStapleAction and isClientOcspCapable. The TlsContext struct includes an ocsp_response_ field of type std::unique_ptr<OcspResponseWrapper> for managing OCSP responses associated with each certificate.\n\n**OCSP Support**: The OCSP module in source/common/tls/ocsp/ provides comprehensive OCSP response handling. The ocsp.h header defines data structures (OcspResponse, BasicOcspResponse, ResponseData, SingleResponse, CertId) that map RFC 6960 ASN.1 structures. OcspResponseWrapperImpl in ocsp.cc and ocsp.h implements the Ssl::OcspResponseWrapper interface, providing methods like create (for parsing DER-encoded OCSP responses), matchesCertificate (matching responses to certificates by serial number), secondsUntilExpiration, isExpired, getThisUpdate, and getNextUpdate.\n\n**ASN.1 Parsing**: The asn1_utility.h and asn1_utility.cc files implement ASN.1 DER parsing utilities specific to OCSP. The Asn1Utility class provides template functions for parsing ASN.1 SEQUENCE OF, optional elements, object identifiers, generalized time, integers, and octet strings. The Asn1OcspUtility class provides specialized parsing functions: parseOcspResponse, parseResponseStatus, parseResponseBytes, parseBasicOcspResponse, parseResponseData, parseSingleResponse, and parseCertId.\n\n**Validation Flow**: When a TLS connection is established, the ContextImpl instantiates a DefaultCertValidator (or custom validator) via CertValidatorFactory. The validator is initialized via initializeSslContexts, which configures X509_STORE objects with trusted CA certificates and CRL information. During the SSL handshake, customVerifyCallback in ContextImpl is invoked, which delegates to the validator's doVerifyCertChain method. This method verifies the certificate chain against configured trust anchors, applies SAN matchers, and checks certificate pinning hashes. ServerContextImpl handles OCSP responses by parsing them with OcspResponseWrapperImpl::create, matching them to certificates by serial number, and stapling them to handshake responses when the client advertises OCSP support.\n\n**Additional Context**: The CertificateValidationContextConfig interface in envoy/ssl/certificate_validation_context_config.h defines configuration accessors for CA certificates, CRLs, SAN matchers, hash lists, and trust verification settings. The configuration is passed through the factory pattern to create validators appropriate to the endpoint's role (client vs server)."
